Edit `platform/browser-extension/src/background.ts`, lines 65-77.

Current code:
```typescript
chrome.tabs.onUpdated.addListener((tabId, changeInfo, tab) => {
  if (changeInfo.status === 'complete' && tab.url) {
    injectPluginsIntoTab(tabId, tab.url)
      .then(() => checkTabChanged(tabId, changeInfo))
      .catch(...);
  } else if (changeInfo.url) {
    checkTabChanged(tabId, changeInfo).catch(...);
  }
});
```

New logic needs TWO events:
1. On `status === 'loading'` — inject adapters (so they run before page JS)
2. On `status === 'complete'` — check tab state (isReady probe happens here)

```typescript
chrome.tabs.onUpdated.addListener((tabId, changeInfo, tab) => {
  if (changeInfo.status === 'loading' && tab.url) {
    // Inject early so adapters are present before page JavaScript runs.
    // This lets plugins cache volatile state (e.g., localStorage tokens)
    // that the host app may delete during initialization.
    injectPluginsIntoTab(tabId, tab.url)
      .catch((err: unknown) => console.warn('[opentabs] early tab injection failed:', err));
  } else if (changeInfo.status === 'complete' && tab.url) {
    // Re-inject (idempotent) and check state after page has fully loaded.
    // isReady() probes run here because plugins depend on page globals
    // and DOM elements that only exist after page JavaScript executes.
    injectPluginsIntoTab(tabId, tab.url)
      .then(() => checkTabChanged(tabId, changeInfo))
      .catch((err: unknown) => console.warn('[opentabs] tab injection failed:', err));
  } else if (changeInfo.url) {
    checkTabChanged(tabId, changeInfo).catch((err: unknown) => console.warn('[opentabs] tab state check failed:', err));
  }
});
```

CRITICAL: `injectPluginsIntoTab` must be IDEMPOTENT — if the adapter is already injected (from the loading event), the complete event's re-injection should be a no-op. Check `platform/browser-extension/src/iife-injection.ts` function `injectPluginsIntoTab` to verify it already handles re-injection gracefully. The IIFE wrapper in `platform/plugin-tools/src/build.ts` checks `globalThis.__openTabs?.adapters?.[pluginName]` and calls teardown before re-registering, so re-injection IS safe.

RISK: At `status:'loading'`, the tab's document may be in the process of being created. `chrome.scripting.executeScript` should still work because it queues execution. Test with the e2e test suite to verify.

SECOND RISK: The `tab.url` might not be available at `status:'loading'`. The `tab` parameter in onUpdated has a `url` property, but Chrome may not populate it until the navigation commits. If `tab.url` is undefined at loading time, we need to use `changeInfo.url` instead (which is present when the URL changes).

Verify all existing E2E tests pass — the Slack plugin and e2e-test plugin should be unaffected because their isReady polling handles the timing gap between injection (loading) and state check (complete).

Edit `plugins/discord/src/discord-api.ts`.

Add a module-level cache variable and modify getAuth() to use it:

```typescript
let cachedAuth: DiscordAuth | null = null;

const getAuth = (): DiscordAuth | null => {
  // Return cached token if available
  if (cachedAuth) return cachedAuth;

  const raw = readLocalStorage('token');
  if (!raw) return null;

  try {
    const token = JSON.parse(raw) as unknown;
    if (typeof token !== 'string' || token.length === 0) return null;
    cachedAuth = { token };
    return cachedAuth;
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
};
```

Also add a cache-clearing mechanism for 401 errors. In the discordApi function, when a 401 is received, clear the cache before throwing:

```typescript
if (response.status === 401 || response.status === 403) {
  cachedAuth = null; // Clear cache on auth failure — token may have been rotated
  throw ToolError.auth(...);
}
```

This ensures:
1. First call reads from localStorage (works at loading time before Discord deletes it)
2. Subsequent calls use the cached value (works after Discord deletes localStorage)
3. Token rotation is handled (401 clears cache, next call retries localStorage/iframe)
